    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>City Was Once Named For a French Province</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Randy Hobler letter on June 4 FYI column notes that explorer Giovanni da Verrazano christened New York Angouleme, after home province of French King Francois I (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In a delightful F.Y.I. item on June 4 (''La Grande Pomme''), a reader asked whether New York City had had any other European names other than ''New Amsterdam.'' You mentioned ''New Orange'' but failed to mention the name that preceded ''New Amsterdam.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In a delightful F.Y.I. item on June 4 (''La Grande Pomme''), a reader asked whether New York City had had any other European names other than ''New Amsterdam.'' You mentioned ''New Orange'' but failed to mention the name that preceded ''New Amsterdam.''</p>
        <p>The explorer Giovanni da Verrazano, commissioned by King Francois I of France, discovered New York and the Hudson River in 1524, 85 years before Henry Hudson explored the river in 1609. At that time, Verrazano christened New York after the home province of King Francois, ''Angouleme.'' We've commemorated Verrazano with a bridge; it's high time we also commemorated him in history textbooks with the first European name bestowed upon our city.</p>
        <p>RANDY HOBLER  Dobbs Ferry, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
